<font color="#FF0000">A FEW THOUGHTS</font><br>
<tt>Tue Dec  2 22:00:53 US/Eastern 1997
</tt><p>
The best way to avoid firefights is to allow others to hold on to their opinions. The purpose of this site is for all viewpoints or opinions to be expressed.<br><br>
What each of us should understand is that many students have formed their opinions prior to reading this site.<br><br>
Our tone and our conduct has much to do with how our points of view are received.<br><br>
Are we going to change each others minds? Not likely. So why not concentrate on telling whatever it is we wish to tell. If we disagree is that so terrible? Point, counterpoint. What is the big deal?<br><br>
When we get caught up in who is right and who is wrong, as a matter of personal prestige, firefights erupt. Can we honestly look at anything that man has created and say that it is absolutely right? Can we look at a person and say that he is all good or all bad? Who really knows all there is to know about the Vietnam War? <br><br>
We sure as hell know all of the arguments. If we knew even one answer we would surely achieve something approaching greatness. If only *our* war was that easy to explain!<br><br>
Compare the war in Vietnam with WWII. Tha ambiguous war and the war that was the &quot;good&quot; war. I daresay that if we were WWII vets we wouldn't be here on this site locked in arguments!<br><br>
If we could leave the politics out of the dialogue for a while, that might be worthwhile. I would like to see personal narratives on this site. What was it like in your part of Vietnam? What was your job? Etc. These are the types of questions I get asked about once a week from kids who are seeking answers.<br><br>
Maybe slowly resuming the dialogue in this way is the answer?<br><br>
Peace,<br><br>
Tom Dier
